column11: FluNet is the World Health Organization's global web-based tool for influenza virological surveillance. Relevant data can be accessed via FluNet functions, 'Download influenza laboratory surveillance data from any week here. Select by: 'Country, area or territory'; Filter by: the country of interest; set the time period to cover the epidemiological-week(s) of interest; and then click 'Display report.' This question will be resolved using the value or sum of values reported in ‘Total number of influenza positive viruses’ or ‘ALL_INF’ for all reporting weeks within the period of interest. Question will be suspended on the last day of the period of interest and resolved when data for the period of interest is released. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: trying a log-linear model (moderately predictive), based on the rising edges of the curves

I was looking for information about the epidemiological week. Found out there are influenza positive and negative viruses. I downloaded the flunet's laboratory surveillance information on Qatar and download the who year's listing on influenza positive viruses. Found out that the latest figure is 116 in week 42 (2017) but there is no clear trend curve in any direction. Then I downloaded previous year's charts and in 2016 in week 46 the number has been 139 and 2015 it was 576 and 2014 it has been 33. So I came up with a resolution that the scope of epidemic is extremely hard to forecast, but I will base my estimation on the fact that 2014 was a massive outbreak. the trend should be decreasing, if there are any lessons learned. In addition Qatar is vaccinating people long before the outbreak.
Shifting a little higher to account for the number of cases in the last few weeks.

As by now recent data is available, I'm basing my forecast on a moving average (4 weeks) and corresponding moving standard deviation. Without knowledge (or even rough idea) of the underlying distribution, I first assume a normal distribution with the estimated parameters, and then adjust for possible outliers, effectively shifting the distribution to higher values (effectively assigning a non-zero probability to the 200-293 category).

Reviewing available history of FluNet data for Quatar (< 3 years): Last time the number of influenza positive specimens [in a week] exceeded 200 was in 2015. There was clear antecedent log-phase. Most recent data is stable to downtrending; at this point even the onset of a new log-phase would be likely to take more than a week to exceed 200 positive specimens per week.
Following @Khalid's data and analysis.

Aggressive vaccination plan plus the blockade which curtails some travel will cut down on the flu cases within the Qatari national and expat white-collar work force. I 've seen some analysis based on the large expat workforce. I believe there could be an issue in the accurately of reporting influenza cases in a poulation of 2.6 million people 88 to 90 % are an uneducated expat labor mostly from under developed , poor countries. I'm not confident that they would be diagnosed in proportion to the upper and white collar classes in Qatar. If influenza became epidemic in the expat community then I believe we could see a big spike in reported flu cases however, I don't think we are there yet. This is a pure statistical reasoning. I have created a probability matrix by category ("less than 27",...) by week for the period of 2012-2017. Then I have calculated the average of the probability between week 43 and week 49. Although recorded in 2015, there might be pattern that once you are above 120 cases, it might lead to higher recordings in the weeks after, which could seem probable since due to the ease of the diseases' transmission more people contaminated with influenza A could lead to more contaminations. At the moment of writing I only see one instance (week 41), but then it stabilises for 2 weeks in a row between 27 and 120.
Reviewing past data for this date range. 2016, with 139, appears to have been an outlier. Adjusting.
I arrived at this from an average of several forecast methods.
Same week last year was 139. Recent weeks’ data suggests a similar trend.

Previous months going back to 2012 have had a spike in terms of number of infections due to the spread of the virus. It is highly unlikely that less than 27 confirmed cases are during one of the highest points of the season. Thus the probability was put at 2%.
Making my best guess based on the flu chart and weather forecasts for Qatar during that week.

To get a baseline forecast I basically just fit a linear model to the values for Week 46 by the values for Week 42 and applied those coefficients to the current value for week 42 and then used the prior deviation of Week 46 values to assign probabilities to each bin. I then took the lower probability values and prorated them to the other bins. I will update later based on further evidence and analysis.

There are substantially more cases at this time of year compared to the previous four. What's the reason? There are some clues - Australia and New Zealand have had a bad year, due to a strain not covered by the annual vaccination, so the Northern Hemisphere is bracing for the worst (even though the vaccination has been reformulated). Although Qatar does not have a cold "winter" as such, the change in weather starting from November does lead to increased respiratory problems, so there could be a seasonal increase in cases. http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/09/12/nhs-fears-worst-flu-season-history/ https://www.statnews.com/2017/10/16/flu-virus-severity/
[note to self: week 42 is 63. Prepare to update substantially on basis of week 43.]

Going back to 2012 flu cases in week 46 have been higher than in the prior four weeks, with the exception of 2014. As well, in 2016, 2015, and 2012 rates were significantly higher (around 2-3 times higher) than the prior four week average. With that in mind I am expecting an uptick in cases over the next few weeks in Qatar but definitely going to keep an eye on case numbers over the next few weeks.
